[5] Taiwan
Date: Wed 12 Nov 2014
Source: The China Post [edited]
http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2014/11/12/421620/CDC-closely.htm


The Centers for Disease Control (CDC) confirmed yesterday [11 Nov 2014] that the recent case of measles stemming from a single family in Nantou continued to expand as a 5th measles case was discovered in an 18 month old boy, making this the most serious case of familial disease clustering in 5 years.

According to CDC deputy director-general Chou Jih-haw, the boy, who is the nephew of the 3rd infected person, was hospitalized for a high fever, with doctors later confirming that he was infected with measles. Chou also said that since the boy had received an MMR vaccination 3 months ago, he showed only minor symptoms and had already be discharged from the local hospital.

Although the CDC believes that the boy will not be as contagious as the other cases, medical staff will keep tracking the health conditions of the 26 people who had been in contact with the boy. In addition to those who had contact with the infected family members, there are a total of 540 people whose conditions are being supervised by the CDC, as they may be infected with the disease. These people will be under observation until 15 Nov 2014.

Based on the CDC's statistics, there have been 26 measles cases this year [2014]. Among them, 18 became infected overseas, including 6 from mainland China, 6 from the Philippines, 2 from Indonesia, 2 from Viet Nam, one from Hong Kong and one from Malaysia. The CDC reminded citizens to take extra care when visiting mainland China and Southeast Asia. If symptoms such as runny nose, rashes and fever appear after traveling to these places, people should go to local hospitals as soon as possible and report their past whereabouts as well as contact history to their doctor.

[byline: Queena Yen]

